This is ACRIS -- Automatically-Controlled Room Illumination System

Born out of a project I worked on over January and February of 2011[1], ACRIS
is a system designed to provide precise control of high-powered LEDs.  It
consists of a set of LED controller boards, which drive LEDs using
constant-current sink drivers and are controlled over an RS-485 network, and a
communications board, which interfaces with a computer over USB and talks to
the LED controllers.  This hardware is very easily controlled via simple serial
commands sent by software.

My goal for ACRIS is to provide a complete stack from base hardware to
software.

Features:
    - Each LED controller supports up to 15 channels, each sinking up to 360mA
    - LED controllers are just 3.2" by 2.3"
    - Status LEDs on the board tell you what the hell is going on
    - CAPACITORS.  ALL THE CAPACITORS.  EVERY SINGLE CAPACITOR.
    - Each Mini LED controller supports up to 5 channels, also at 360mA each
    - Mini controllers are just 1.4" by .88"
    - Communications board provides two RS-485 outputs and is 1.35" by 1.2"
    - LED controllers have a bootloader, so you can program a new main
      application, set the addresses of various controllers, and set
      the application baud rate all over the RS-485 network!
    - You can even control which devices you program; you can act on single
      devices, blocks of devices, or all devices at once!

This repository has a lot of stuff that's continually being updated.  Nothing
is tested at the moment, but I'm planning to have boards in by the second week
of August 2011.  For up-to-date information, my website
(http://jwcxz.com/projects/acris) is probably the best place to look.

[1] http://next-make.mit.edu/wiki/Main_Page
